00:01:33.160 --> 00:01:37.320
that you tell them,
stories that you weave?

00:01:37.320 --> 00:01:39.230
Do you find seeds
in that that could

00:01:39.230 --> 00:01:41.480
be appropriate for
a broader audience?

00:01:41.480 --> 00:01:45.960
PAT ROTHFUSS: Well, let
me do the first one first.

00:01:45.960 --> 00:01:50.240
I do, actually, with my
little boy, my oldest,

00:01:50.240 --> 00:01:53.830
I started telling him
stories years ago.

00:01:53.830 --> 00:01:59.990
We would sit down, and I would
tell him a little adventure

00:01:59.990 --> 00:02:00.990
story.

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:06.350
And at first, it was just
sort of a story about a boy,

00:02:06.350 --> 00:02:09.190
and then it suddenly
it was kind of him,

00:02:09.190 --> 00:02:11.490
but sometimes it was not him.

00:02:11.490 --> 00:02:13.780
And it would be
centered around whatever

00:02:13.780 --> 00:02:17.040
he was fixated on in the moment.

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:21.000
For a while, skunks were the
coolest possible thing ever,

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:25.590
and so it wasn't just the
story about this little boy,

00:02:25.590 --> 00:02:29.010
he was a skunk boy,
so the story had

00:02:29.010 --> 00:02:32.980
better center around his
ability to spray animals

00:02:32.980 --> 00:02:37.770
with this stank, or it would
not be a satisfactory story.

00:02:37.770 --> 00:02:39.950
Then he was into lizards,
and of course, the story

00:02:39.950 --> 00:02:42.610
better center around
him changing color

00:02:42.610 --> 00:02:47.190
so that he could defend
himself or scare people away.

00:02:47.190 --> 00:02:49.680
Now, do these directly
translate into stuff

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:51.320
that's good for a fantasy novel?

00:02:51.320 --> 00:02:53.170
No, no, not really.

00:02:53.170 --> 00:02:56.720
But it actually
goes the other way.

00:02:56.720 --> 00:03:01.820
It's because storytelling
is pretty old hat for me,

00:03:01.820 --> 00:03:05.260
and that goes all the
way back to any table top

00:03:05.260 --> 00:03:07.970
D&amp;D or any role-playing games.

00:03:07.970 --> 00:03:12.490
It's really just
improvisational storytelling.

00:03:12.490 --> 00:03:16.365
I have LARPed, which is
real improv storytelling.

00:03:20.390 --> 00:03:27.045
It's all similar aspects
of the storytelling craft.

00:03:27.045 --> 00:03:28.420
I've been thinking
about it a lot

00:03:28.420 --> 00:03:30.770
lately, because it's
a ton of fun with him,

00:03:30.770 --> 00:03:33.750
and they used to be
little standalone stories,

00:03:33.750 --> 00:03:38.640
and then they started getting
connected where he would say,

00:03:38.640 --> 00:03:40.130
well he would use
the magic rope.

00:03:40.130 --> 00:03:42.470
And I'm like, what
magic rope is that?

00:03:42.470 --> 00:03:46.070
He's like, the magic rope he
found before, and I'm like,

00:03:46.070 --> 00:03:49.440
right, OK, yeah, that's
right, there was a magic rope.

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:54.730
And so now, he's having a little
D&amp;D adventure with a continuing

00:03:54.730 --> 00:03:57.730
character that is him kind of.

00:03:57.730 --> 00:04:01.890
And I have a lot of
fun with it, and I've

00:04:01.890 --> 00:04:04.220
been thinking of trying
to come up with some way

00:04:04.220 --> 00:04:07.850
that I could bring that
to other people who aren't

00:04:07.850 --> 00:04:11.860
storytellers by their nature,
that's not their craft.

00:04:11.860 --> 00:04:17.410
Like a series of cards that
you could use as storytelling

00:04:17.410 --> 00:04:22.790
framework where it's like a
setting card, it's a forest,

00:04:22.790 --> 00:04:26.610
it's a castle, it's a
cave, what's in there?

00:04:26.610 --> 00:04:31.210
Well, there's webs, it's
night time, it's raining.

00:04:31.210 --> 00:04:34.200
And these things that
could give somebody

00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:38.640
who doesn't do this
for a living a way

00:04:38.640 --> 00:04:42.382
to have a storytelling
experience with their kid.

00:04:42.382 --> 00:04:43.920
But you know, I
need another project

00:04:43.920 --> 00:04:46.030
right now like I need
a whole in the head,

00:04:46.030 --> 00:04:48.331
so I've been pushing off that.

00:04:48.331 --> 00:04:50.080
MALE SPEAKER: I like
what you said, there.

00:04:50.080 --> 00:04:52.496
I think there's really a lot
to be said about improvising,

00:04:52.496 --> 00:04:54.080
and them whole
idea of, yes, and,

00:04:54.080 --> 00:04:56.780
and continuing with the story.

00:04:56.780 --> 00:04:59.820
Now, with that the
origin for Mr. Whiffle

00:04:59.820 --> 00:05:02.450
as well from stories
told to your children

00:05:02.450 --> 00:05:06.540
PAT ROTHFUSS: No, that was
a story that I originally

00:05:06.540 --> 00:05:10.860
told to my girlfriend
back in grad school.

00:05:10.860 --> 00:05:14.010
Grad school was a
dark time for me,

00:05:14.010 --> 00:05:17.920
and so we were both living
out in Washington state,

00:05:17.920 --> 00:05:19.410
and she was going
to bed earlier,

00:05:19.410 --> 00:05:21.230
and I was going to bed later.

00:05:21.230 --> 00:05:23.680
And one night she
said, tell me a story.

00:05:23.680 --> 00:05:28.290
We had separate bedrooms, and
so I went into her bedroom,

00:05:28.290 --> 00:05:31.630
and she's like, tell me a
story before I go to sleep.

00:05:31.630 --> 00:05:33.280
So I said, once
upon a time, there

00:05:33.280 --> 00:05:35.490
was a princess who lived
in a marzipan castle,

00:05:35.490 --> 00:05:38.270
starting with the grossest,
most saccharin sort

00:05:38.270 --> 00:05:41.560
of children's story I
could possibly imagine.

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:45.810
And it infuriated me so
much when it came out

00:05:45.810 --> 00:05:48.810
of my own mouth that
twisted it into something

00:05:48.810 --> 00:05:50.379
dark and terrible.

00:05:50.379 --> 00:05:52.920
And then I finished it, and I
thought, that was a good story,

00:05:52.920 --> 00:05:53.960
I feel good about that.

00:05:53.960 --> 00:05:56.043
And she was laying there
in bed, and she was like,

00:05:56.043 --> 00:05:59.080
now I can't sleep.

00:05:59.080 --> 00:06:02.010
And so I'm like, OK, and then
I put a different ending on it

00:06:02.010 --> 00:06:05.830
that was even more
saccharine and awful

00:06:05.830 --> 00:06:08.700
than the first one that
had started to piss me off.

00:06:08.700 --> 00:06:10.770
And so then I put
a third one on it

00:06:10.770 --> 00:06:13.390
that was much worse
than the other.

00:06:13.390 --> 00:06:16.710
And it was a fun story,
and I told it to somebody

00:06:16.710 --> 00:06:19.390
the next day, and one of
them was an illustrator.

00:06:19.390 --> 00:06:22.020
We did a cartoon in the
campus paper, and he said,

00:06:22.020 --> 00:06:23.020
I'd love to draw that.

00:06:23.020 --> 00:06:25.940
So I took a couple hours
and I scripted it out,

00:06:25.940 --> 00:06:30.530
and nothing came of it for five
years until "Name of the Wind"

00:06:30.530 --> 00:06:33.370
was already published, and
then somebody approached me,

00:06:33.370 --> 00:06:36.720
the lovely folks at Subterranean
Press, "Name of the Wind"

00:06:36.720 --> 00:06:42.990
had been out like a week and
a half, and Bill emails me,

00:06:42.990 --> 00:06:45.250
and he's like, so,
what do you want

00:06:45.250 --> 00:06:47.690
to do that you've never
had a chance to do?

00:06:47.690 --> 00:06:48.660
Come do it with us.

00:06:48.660 --> 00:06:51.710
And I'm like, I got
a weird kids story,

00:06:51.710 --> 00:06:53.230
and he's like, let's do that.

00:06:53.230 --> 00:06:55.810
And if it wasn't
for him it never

00:06:55.810 --> 00:06:58.020
would have seen
the light of day.

00:06:58.020 --> 00:06:59.940
MALE SPEAKER: So
marzipan castle,

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:03.100
are there any other fancy
tropes that you particularly

00:07:03.100 --> 00:07:05.740
hate apart from stew and--

00:07:05.740 --> 00:07:08.750
PAT ROTHFUSS: I love stew.

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:12.560
That's Scalzi that has a problem
with stew and fantasy novels.

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:18.730
I hate the feeling of
picking up any book

00:07:18.730 --> 00:07:22.920
and reading it, being excited
about reading a new book,

00:07:22.920 --> 00:07:25.760
and feeling like I've
read the book before.

00:07:25.760 --> 00:07:27.410
And if you read
a lot of fantasy,

00:07:27.410 --> 00:07:30.050
you know what I'm talking about.

00:07:30.050 --> 00:07:33.150
And I'm not saying-- I've
done a couple of interviews,

00:07:33.150 --> 00:07:37.380
and I end up quoted
kind of out of context.

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:38.950
I think there's one
up on-- it might

00:07:38.950 --> 00:07:44.020
have been io9 or something--
where the big pull quote is,

00:07:44.020 --> 00:07:49.040
Rothfuss says fantasy has to
move past dragons and goblins.

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:54.600
And I'm like, whoa, whoa,
whoa, that's a little extreme,

00:07:54.600 --> 00:07:57.070
it's that we need more than.

00:07:57.070 --> 00:07:59.570
It's like if you're
going to do that,

00:07:59.570 --> 00:08:03.490
you should do it in a way
that hasn't been done before.

00:08:03.490 --> 00:08:05.530
Oh yeah, I think I
took a crack at dwarfs

00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:07.770
an elves with long
bows and stuff,

00:08:07.770 --> 00:08:09.530
so it really looked
like I was either

00:08:09.530 --> 00:08:13.720
taking a pot shot at Martin, or
Tolkien, and that's not true.

00:08:13.720 --> 00:08:16.780
Because Martin and Tolkien have
written some really amazing

00:08:16.780 --> 00:08:22.540
stories, but there's a lot
of people who have maybe

00:08:22.540 --> 00:08:26.870
recycled some of those troops
past their sell by date.

00:08:26.870 --> 00:08:29.650
MALE SPEAKER: Well even having
a story told in the first-person

00:08:29.650 --> 00:08:30.822
was a pretty good--

00:08:30.822 --> 00:08:33.030
PAT ROTHFUSS: Yeah, although
I wasn't the first there

00:08:33.030 --> 00:08:33.850
by any means.

00:08:33.850 --> 00:08:37.309
Joan Vinge was writing
brilliant first-person,

00:08:37.309 --> 00:08:42.500
Robin Hobb wrote brilliant
first-person fantasy, too.

00:08:42.500 --> 00:08:46.630
And honestly, first-person is
the most natural storytelling

00:08:46.630 --> 00:08:47.870
form.

00:08:47.870 --> 00:08:51.000
If you are talking to
anybody during lunch today,

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:58.680
you don't say, yesterday, she
was, you say, yesterday, I was,

00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:01.660
that's the most natural
storytelling form there is.

00:09:01.660 --> 00:09:04.450
But you're right, it doesn't
show up in novels as much.

00:09:04.450 --> 00:09:06.150
MALE SPEAKER: Now,
Terry Pratchett,

00:09:06.150 --> 00:09:08.430
one of your favorite
authors, well-loved

00:09:08.430 --> 00:09:11.320
among this crowd as
well, he ceremoniously

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:14.335
deletes every draft copy of
his books and manuscripts

00:09:14.335 --> 00:09:16.050
before they come out.

00:09:16.050 --> 00:09:17.170
Do you do the same?

00:09:17.170 --> 00:09:19.820
Is there a university vying
for the Rothfuss papers,

00:09:19.820 --> 00:09:21.920
the early drafts?

00:09:21.920 --> 00:09:23.730
PAT ROTHFUSS: It
kind of horrified me,

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:26.240
and it broke my heart
a little hearing that.

00:09:26.240 --> 00:09:28.240
But I read the same article
where he said, yeah,

00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:32.060
he goes, I delete every other
thing after it's published.

00:09:32.060 --> 00:09:35.120
He goes, let the
literary analysis

00:09:35.120 --> 00:09:39.130
get real jobs or
something like that.

00:09:39.130 --> 00:09:42.330
And that's his right,
it's the equivalent

00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:43.330
of burning your papers.

00:09:46.360 --> 00:09:50.580
No, I keep a lot
of my old drafts,

00:09:50.580 --> 00:09:54.700
the computer file with "Name
of the Wind" in it has, like,

00:09:54.700 --> 00:10:00.370
600 embedded
comments where I make

00:10:00.370 --> 00:10:03.340
note of what
particular words mean,

00:10:03.340 --> 00:10:06.920
or sometimes it's just,
leave this sentence alone

00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:09.770
because the meter is good
so that if I'm revising it,

00:10:09.770 --> 00:10:12.140
I don't screw up that nice
little piece in there.

00:10:12.140 --> 00:10:15.460
Sometimes it's, this is actually
a reference to something that's

00:10:15.460 --> 00:10:17.610
happening in book
three, so if you

00:10:17.610 --> 00:10:21.846
forgot this, Rothfuss,
don't change this either.

00:10:21.846 --> 00:10:24.360
Sometimes one of my beta
readers has given me

00:10:24.360 --> 00:10:27.830
a really funny comment
that I don't want to lose,

00:10:27.830 --> 00:10:30.206
and I'll tuck it in there.

00:10:30.206 --> 00:10:32.610
I get a lot of great
peanut gallery comments

00:10:32.610 --> 00:10:34.900
from my beta readers.

00:10:34.900 --> 00:10:36.970
MALE SPEAKER: So, is
there any hope of those

00:10:36.970 --> 00:10:39.370
comments seeing the light of
day or an extended edition,

00:10:39.370 --> 00:10:42.320
things that may have
gotten in editing?

00:10:42.320 --> 00:10:44.810
PAT ROTHFUSS: There will
never be a director's cut.

00:10:44.810 --> 00:10:46.962
This is the director's cut.

00:10:46.962 --> 00:10:50.080
What you have is the
best possible book.

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:51.930
If we cut something,
it's because it really

00:10:51.930 --> 00:10:54.300
shouldn't be in there.

00:10:54.300 --> 00:10:57.810
But that said, an
annotated version

00:10:57.810 --> 00:11:03.300
for the people who perhaps
enjoy the book beyond all reason

00:11:03.300 --> 00:11:03.800
or sense?

00:11:07.609 --> 00:11:09.400
I have a delightful
number of those people,

00:11:09.400 --> 00:11:11.700
I am one of those
people, and you really

00:11:11.700 --> 00:11:14.030
want to know what
this phrase actually

00:11:14.030 --> 00:11:15.910
means, what the
etymology of the words

00:11:15.910 --> 00:11:19.290
is, and a few of
the little jokes.

00:11:19.290 --> 00:11:21.020
And it's not giving
anything away,

00:11:21.020 --> 00:11:24.420
in the very first pages
of "Name of the Wind"

00:11:24.420 --> 00:11:28.300
when you meet the
troop and they're

00:11:28.300 --> 00:11:31.750
talking about them
setting up, and there's

00:11:31.750 --> 00:11:37.060
Marion and his wife who are
doing a string-puppet show.

00:11:37.060 --> 00:11:43.270
And what would Marion wife,
what would his wife's name be?

00:11:43.270 --> 00:11:43.785
What is it?

00:11:43.785 --> 00:11:44.660
AUDIENCE: Marionette.

00:11:44.660 --> 00:11:46.390
PAT ROTHFUSS: Marionette, right?

00:11:46.390 --> 00:11:46.890
See?

00:11:46.890 --> 00:11:52.190
And that's just there for me
and maybe you, if you catch it,

00:11:52.190 --> 00:11:54.910
but the books are full of that.

00:11:54.910 --> 00:11:58.220
I wanted to put like
100 things on every page

00:11:58.220 --> 00:12:00.480
so that if you caught
two, you'd be like,

00:12:00.480 --> 00:12:02.450
oh, there's some
cool stuff in here.

00:12:02.450 --> 00:12:04.230
And then when you
read it again, there's

00:12:04.230 --> 00:12:06.021
some stuff that you
really can't appreciate

00:12:06.021 --> 00:12:07.880
until you're reading
it the second time

00:12:07.880 --> 00:12:09.970
or until you've read
the second book,

00:12:09.970 --> 00:12:11.580
or until you've
read the third book.

00:12:11.580 --> 00:12:13.430
So those things are
waiting for people.

00:12:13.430 --> 00:12:14.805
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah
even allusions

00:12:14.805 --> 00:12:17.560
to Dune I found on a repeated
reading, which was cool

00:12:17.560 --> 00:12:19.380
PAT ROTHFUSS: Something
about Dun, really?

00:12:19.380 --> 00:12:20.963
MALE SPEAKER: Sand
worms I don't know.

00:12:20.963 --> 00:12:24.520
PAT ROTHFUSS: Oh,
yeah, there is, yeah.

